{
  "text": "The results of this paper can be compared to those of [CITATION_1] , although the empirical set-ups differ markedly. Fagerberg looks at the impact of national and international spillovers on export performance in the entire market of his sample of ten OECD countries, while this paper looks at the impact on the bilateral trade balance. Fagerberg uses two linkage variables as independent variables. The first is the sum of domestic and international linkages and the second expresses international linkages over total linkages. The first variable is positive and significant, while the second is negative and significant. This means that domestic linkages are more important than international ones (this is in accordance with the present paper), but it is difficult to conclude whether international linkages just matter less or whether they do not matter at all (as it is the case in this paper for most sectors).",
  "citation_candidates": [
